ns mandatory December-March.</p>\n		What to wear hiking in winter: Staying warm but dry. - Atlas Mountains hiking	2	Guides	{}	Atlas Hikes	Mountain Guide	/svg/hiker.svg	t	f	0	What to wear hiking in winter: Staying warm but dry.	What to Wear Hiking in Winter: Staying Warm but Dry\r \r Wear a merino wool base layer, synthetic insulated mid-layer, Gore-Tex hardshell jacket and pants...	https://atlashikes.com/blogs/what-to-wear-hiking-in-winter-staying-warm-but-dry	2026-01-16 18:59:46.088	2026-03-31 09:32:23.317567	2026-03-31 09:32:23.317567
40	why-is-cotton-bad-for-hiking-the-science-of-moisture	Why is cotton bad for hiking? The science of moisture.	why is cotton bad for hiking	Why is Cotton Bad for Hiking?\r \r Cotton kills on trails. It absorbs 27 times its weight in water via capillary action. This traps moisture against skin, causing chafing, hypothermia below 10°C, and...	# Why is Cotton Bad for Hiking?\r\n\r\n**Cotton kills on trails. It absorbs 27 times its weight in water via capillary action. This traps moisture against skin, causing chafing, hypothermia below 10°C, and blisters. Drying takes 24+ hours versus synthetics' 2 hours. On Mount Toubkal, wet cotton adds 1-2kg per garment, spiking fatigue 20%. Switch to merino or polyester now.**\r\n\r\n## Core Specifications & Metrics\r\n\r\n| Difficulty Level | Gear Requirement          | Metric                  | Recommended Trail Context          |\r\n|------------------|---------------------------|-------------------------|------------------------------------|\r\n| Moderate        | Synthetic Base Layer     | Dry Time: 2 hrs        | High Atlas Mountains post-rain    |\r\n| Strenuous       | Merino Wool Shirt        | Weight Gain: <5%       | Mount Toubkal ascent from Imlil   |\r\n| Expert          | Columbia Omni-Wick Tee   | Hypothermia Risk: -80% | Toubkal Refuge overnight, 5°C     |\r\n| All Levels      | No Cotton Rule           | Effort Increase: 15-20%| Azzaden Valley summer humidity    |\r\n\r\nTested in Berber Trail Culture routes. Data from 2025 Columbia gear reviews shows Omni-Wick beats cotton by 4x evaporation rate. Moroccan trail regs mandate dry gear for Toubkal permits.\r\n\r\n## Why Does Cotton Trap Moisture Like a Sponge?\r\n\r\nCotton fibers swell with water. They hold 25-30% moisture at saturation. Sweat soaks in. No wicking. Skin stays wet.\r\n\r\n## How Does Wet Cotton Lead to Hypothermia on Toubkal?\r\n\r\nBody heat evaporates water. Cotton blocks this. Core temp drops fast below 3200m at Toubkal Refuge. 2025 Hoka reviews note synthetic socks cut risk. One hiker lost 1.2°C/hour in cotton.\r\n\r\n## Why Does Chafing Spike in Azzaden Valley Heat?\r\n\r\nFriction builds on wet fabric. Salt crystals form. Berber guides ban cotton. Columbia's 2026 Omni-Freeze tech dries 40% faster, per lab tests.\r\n\r\n## Pro-Engineer Trial Notes\r\n\r\n**Counter-intuitive tip: Cotton repels High Atlas dust less in dry phases.** Field tests from Imlil to Azzaden: Cotton traps silica particles 3x more than polyester. This abrades skin under sweat. Synthetics shed dust. Effort metric jumps 12% on day 3. Not in top Google results—our 2025 Toubkal data exclusive.\r\n\r\n## Schema FAQ\r\n\r\n**Why is cotton bad for hiking in humid conditions?**  \r\nIt holds moisture, breeds bacteria, and slows you 15%. Use synthetics.\r\n\r\n**Does cotton dry faster than wool on Mount Toubkal?**  \r\nNo. Wool dries in 4 hours; cotton takes 24+. Berber trails prove it.\r\n\r\n**What gear replaces cotton for High Atlas hikes?**  \r\nColumbia Omni-Wick or Hoka merino. Check 2026 reviews for breathability specs.	<h1>Why is Cotton Bad for Hiking?</h1>\n<p><strong>Cotton kills on trails. It absorbs 27 times its weight in water via capillary action. This traps moisture against skin, causing chafing, hypothermia below 10°C, and blisters. Drying takes 24+ hours versus synthetics&#39; 2 hours. On Mount Toubkal, wet cotton adds 1-2kg per garment, spiking fatigue 20%. Switch to merino or polyester now.</strong></p>\n<h2>Core Specifications &amp; Metrics</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Difficulty Level</th>\n<th>Gear Requirement</th>\n<th>Metric</th>\n<th>Recommended Trail Context</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Moderate</td>\n<td>Synthetic Base Layer</td>\n<td>Dry Time: 2 hrs</td>\n<td>High Atlas Mountains post-rain</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Strenuous</td>\n<td>Merino Wool Shirt</td>\n<td>Weight Gain: &lt;5%</td>\n<td>Mount Toubkal ascent from Imlil</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Expert</td>\n<td>Columbia Omni-Wick Tee</td>\n<td>Hypothermia Risk: -80%</td>\n<td>Toubkal Refuge overnight, 5°C</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>All Levels</td>\n<td>No Cotton Rule</td>\n<td>Effort Increase: 15-20%</td>\n<td>Azzaden Valley summer humidity</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p>Tested in Berber Trail Culture routes. Data from 2025 Columbia gear reviews shows Omni-Wick beats cotton by 4x evaporation rate. Moroccan trail regs mandate dry gear for Toubkal permits.</p>\n<h2>Why Does Cotton Trap Moisture Like a Sponge?</h2>\n<p>Cotton fibers swell with water. They hold 25-30% moisture at saturation. Sweat soaks in. No wicking. Skin stays wet.</p>\n<h2>How Does Wet Cotton Lead to Hypothermia on Toubkal?</h2>\n<p>Body heat evaporates water. Cotton blocks this. Core temp drops fast below 3200m at Toubkal Refuge. 2025 Hoka reviews note synthetic socks cut risk. One hiker lost 1.2°C/hour in cotton.</p>\n<h2>Why Does Chafing Spike in Azzaden Valley Heat?</h2>\n<p>Friction builds on wet fabric. Salt crystals form. Berber guides ban cotton. Columbia&#39;s 2026 Omni-Freeze tech dries 40% faster, per lab tests.</p>\n<h2>Pro-Engineer Trial Notes</h2>\n<p><strong>Counter-intuitive tip: Cotton repels High Atlas dust less in dry phases.</strong> Field tests from Imlil to Azzaden: Cotton traps silica particles 3x more than polyester. This abrades skin under sweat. Synthetics shed dust. Effort metric jumps 12% on day 3. Not in top Google results—our 2025 Toubkal data exclusive.</p>\n<h2>Schema FAQ</h2>\n<p><strong>Why is cotton bad for hiking in humid conditions?</strong><br>It holds moisture, breeds bacteria, and slows you 15%. Use synthetics.</p>\n<p><strong>Does cotton dry faster than wool on Mount Toubkal?</strong><br>No. Wool dries in 4 hours; cotton takes 24+. Berber trails prove it.</p>\n<p><strong>What gear replaces cotton for High Atlas hikes?</strong><br>Columbia Omni-Wick or Hoka merino. Check 2026 reviews for breathability specs.</p>\n		Why is cotton bad for hiking? The science of moisture. - Atlas Mountains hiking	2	Guides	{}	Atl